Former Eskom CEO Brian Molefe is set to return to his former job at the power utility on Monday.Eskom board spokesperson Khulani Qoma confirmed on Friday. According to Qoma, the decision was made in the last few days from various conversations and consultations.This follows much controversy around Molefe receiving a R30-million pension payout from the power utility.Acting Eskom CEO Matshela Koko, who took over Molefe after he resigned told ANN7 they are looking forward to having Molefe back at Eskom.Molefe announced his resignation as CEO of the power utility in January. In a statement released, Molefe attacked former public protector Thuli Madonsela s State of Capture, which had labelled him as being corrupt because of his close ties with the Gupta family.Molefe cited that his decision to resign is based on the interests of the utility and the public as a whole. I have, in the interests of good corporate governance, decided to leave my employ at Eskom from 1 January 2017. I do so voluntarily: indeed I wish to pay tribute to the unfailing support I have had since I took up office form the chairman, the Board and with those with whom it has been my privilege to work. Together we brought Eskom back from the brink, Molefe said in a statement.Parliament in February confirmed the nomination of Molefe as African National Congress (ANC) Member of Parliament.Parliament confirms the resignation of #BrianMolefe as a Member of Parliament effective from Sunday. @ANN7tv&mdash; Kalden O Lachungpa (@KaldenOngmu) May 12, 2017&nbsp;TNA Reporter 